\pard\sb240\sa60\keepn\nowidctlpar\qj\b\i\f0\fs24 Specialization\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qj\b0\i0\f1\fs20 All players start as a generic \lquote townsfolk\rquote . During the course of their adventures players are awarded \lquote favor\rquote  points, for role playing their current role well. \lquote Favor\rquote  points can be used to buy a specialization. A player does not have to roleplay precisely their specialisation, however they must rp at the same level of adeptness. For instance a 'townsfolk' player is free to roleplay that they are a gypsy and prefer to live in the woods. However if they roleplay that they are a grand archimage without having specialised through at least past apprentice they shall not be eligable for reward points.\par
\par
One can only specialize in the presence of a mentor of the same or deeper specialization. Skills come from specialization.\par
\par
A townsfolk can specialize to become a student, soldier, sailor or rogue. Students can specialize to study magic, etc. Leveling is independent of specialization, so it is possible to be a level 10 knight and defeat a level 30 student.\par
\par
The deeper the level of specialization, the more specialization points are required to advance to the next depth. Dual specialization is possible, however it reduces the depth to which one can advance. To advance to the first depth requires one \lquote favor\rquote  point, to advance to the second depth requires two \lquote favor\rquote  points, to advance to the third and final depth requires three \lquote favor\rquote  points. Only seven favor points may be used in this way, restricting the number of specializations achievable.\par
